body:
Over at oxyplot we are facing a kind of strange [issue](https://github.com/oxyplot/oxyplot/issues/1573) with our `SkiaRenderContext`, which is based on SkiaSharp 1.68.1.1.

### High-Level Issue

Basically, inside `SkiaRenderContext`, we are [caching](https://github.com/oxyplot/oxyplot/blob/7329013d6f48331e42b81c4315cd13fb5a82bb8f/Source/OxyPlot.SkiaSharp/SkiaRenderContext.cs#L845) instances of `SKTypeface` to reuse them during the rendering operation. This works fine in general. The problem arises when we create and dispose a second instance of `SkiaRenderContext`, which during its disposal will [dispose](https://github.com/oxyplot/oxyplot/blob/7329013d6f48331e42b81c4315cd13fb5a82bb8f/Source/OxyPlot.SkiaSharp/SkiaRenderContext.cs#L473) all the cached fonts it used. From that point on, the text rendering of the first `SkiaRenderContext` will be broken, even though this was never disposed itself.

_(The use case here could be: export a plot using one of the SkiaSharp-based exporters while displaying the plot in a SkiaSharp-based PlotView)_

### Repro

I managed to reproduce the issue using the following minimized example:

        public void TestTypefaceDisposal()
        {
            using var bitmap = new SKBitmap(100, 60);
            using var canvas = new SKCanvas(bitmap);
            canvas.Clear(SKColors.White);

            var minimumRenderContext = new MinimumRenderContext();

            // this draws correctly
            minimumRenderContext.DrawText(new SKPoint(20, 20), "OxyPlot", canvas);

            // create and dispose a completely unrelated SKTypeface instance
            SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Courier New").Dispose();

            // this does NOT render correctly
            minimumRenderContext.DrawText(new SKPoint(20, 40), "OxyPlot", canvas);

            using var fileStream = File.OpenWrite("test.png");
            using var skStream = new SKManagedWStream(fileStream);
            SKPixmap.Encode(skStream, bitmap, SKEncodedImageFormat.Png, 0);
        }

        private class MinimumRenderContext
        {
            private SKTypeface cachedTypeFace;

            public void DrawText(SKPoint point, string text, SKCanvas canvas)
            {
                this.cachedTypeFace ??= SKTypeface.FromFamilyName("Courier New");
                using var paint = new SKPaint() { Typeface = this.cachedTypeFace };
                canvas.DrawText(text, point, paint);
            }
        }

### Expected Result

I would expect both lines to be identically rendered in Courier New. 

### Actual Result

This code above gives the following output in `test.png`:
![test](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18097859/82657436-a558ba80-9c25-11ea-886c-9bbbcb4b7694.png)

Obviously the second line is rendered in a different font. Depending on the circumstances, this can have more serious effects including missing glyphs.

It seems that disposing a `SKTypeface` instance can break other existing instances that share the same font family, weight etc.

Is this a bug? Or am I just not supposed to cache `SKTypeface` instances? I did not find any documentation suggesting that, and I read somewhere that caching is recommended for performance, though I can't find the source atm...
